{"questionId":"13999","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following diagram shows part of the graph of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"f\">\n  <mi>f</mi>\n</math></span> with <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span>-intercept (5, 0) and <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n</math></span>-intercept (0, 8).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/f7195d4a565ae381c6fd64a652ffd85f0e9f83fb.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n</math></span>-intercept of the graph of&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"f\\left( x \\right) + 3\">\n  <mi>f</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>3</mn>\n</math></span>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n</math></span>-intercept is 11&nbsp; &nbsp;(accept (0, 11) )&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1 N1</strong></em>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"13999","referenceCode":"19M.1.SL.TZ2.S_4a.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the y -intercept of the graph of f ( x ) + 3 .","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.8—Transformations of graphs, composite transformations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}